\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Night. Even at night the city rumbles and roars. Traffic drones on the motorway that circles the center. There are machines and engines that can never be allowed to rest. And even the breathing and snoring and whisperi
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ng must add to the din. And the running of water through pipes, and the humming of electricity, and the chatter of televisions watched by people who can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
t sleep, and dogs that bark and cats that yowl. And there are the owls, as always, hooting as they fly\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
over Crow Road and Heston Park. Hello, Owls. Hoot. Hoot. I try to hoot like an owl but it sounds nothing like an owl.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 I thought I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 d write the story of the Underworld in the first person, and say, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I did this and I did that.\'94\loch\f0  But somehow it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s better to writ\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 e this in the third person, to say, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Mina did this and Mina did that.\'94\loch\f0  I write it by moonlight, to the hooting of the owls.
