And so one day our heroine, Mina, who thought she was so clever and strong, arrived at Corinthian Avenu\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 e. As Karl\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s taxi drove away, Mina walked hand in hand with her mum towards the glass doorway.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 As they stepped inside, a woman came to them.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 m Mrs. Milligan,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  she said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And you must be Mina!\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes, I suppose I must,\'94\loch\f0  said Mina.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 She is,\'94\loch\f0  said Mina\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s mum, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 and I am Mrs. McKee.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mrs. Milligan smiled kindly, and led them into a small and brightly lit office. She filled in a form and asked Mina\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s mum to sign. She opened a file from St. Bede\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s. Mina sighed and scowled.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Relax, Mina,\'94\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 said Mrs. Milligan. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re not here to judge you. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
re here to help.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She closed the notes and smiled.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 Didn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t really fit in, did you, dear?\'94\loch\f0  she said.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Hardly.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 One system can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t fit us all, can it? We know that here, Mina.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Do you?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mina wanted this wo\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 man to be like Palaver or Trench. She wanted her to be like Scullery or like THE HEAD TEACHER. But she was like none of them.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 We know you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re only here for a visit,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Mrs. Milligan. \'93\loch\f0 But perhaps you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ll like us enough to stay a little longer.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 Or perha\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ps not,\'94\loch\f0  responded the girl.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mrs. Milligan smiled sweetly. Mina\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s mum flashed her eyes at Mina. Mina looked away. She was trying to be careless and free, but she was confused, and she was trembling inside. and she felt weirdly quiet, weirdly shy. She wante\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 d to run away.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mrs. Milligan showed them where the toilets were and where the lunchroom was. Everywhere was neat and clean. There was a cooling smell of lavender. There were lots of books on lots of shelves. There were kids\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0  paintings on the walls. There w\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ere stories and poems hanging beside them.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Soon other kids began to arrive in taxis and minibuses. There were adults in T-shirts and jeans with their names on tags that hung around their necks.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mrs. Milligan took them to Room B12, a room with woodblock flo\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 oring, a window with white net curtains on it, tables and red plastic chairs in a ring. One of the walls had a mural painted on it 
\hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  a huge rain forest with monkeys and snakes and butterflies and frogs. The names of the artists were painted along the bott\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 m edge: Daniela, Eric, Patrick, Steepy\~
\hich\f0 \'85
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 We do a lot of art here,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Mrs. Milligan. \'93\loch\f0 Malcolm\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s an expert at it. He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll be here soon.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mina shrugged.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 I hear you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re something of an expert, too,\'94\loch\f0  said Mrs. Milligan.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Expert!\'94\loch\f0  grunted Mina.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She rolled her \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 eyes at her mum, who whispered,
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Mina!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Then Malcolm arrived. He wore blue jeans, a red shirt, a silver bracelet on his wrist.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 m Malcolm,\'94\loch\f0  he said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mina said nothing. Mina\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s mum nudged her:
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s Malcolm. You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re\~\hich\f0 \'85\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And you must be Mina,\'94\loch\f0  continued Malc\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 olm.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve been looking forward to meeting you.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mina lowered her eyes. She shuffled her feet.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She felt her lips curling downward like on a cartoon face.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 m so sorry,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said her mum. \'93\loch\f0 She\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s not usually so\~\hich\f0 \'85\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s all right!\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Malcolm. \'93\loch\f0 First day, new place, bit shy. She\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ll be fine once she gets to know us. Ah, Harry! Come and meet Mina.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Harry was a short boy in a blue anorak, with lank hair and perplexed eyes. He came towards them. He nodded shyly at M\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ina. He held a book out to Malcolm.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I b-brung it,\'94\loch\f0  he said.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 It? Ah, Buddha! Thank you!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 He took the book and fanned it open for Mina.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 One of the first great graphic novels,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 As good as they say, Harry?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 A-aye, Malcolm,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  stammered Harry. \'93\loch\f0 Aye!\loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mina turned away, as if she disapproved.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Personally, I prefer the complexity of words,\'94\loch\f0  she said. She hated herself even as she was saying it. She had read the book in Malcolm\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s hands, and she liked it a lot. But she couldn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t stop herself from blatherin\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 g on and showing off and trying to show she was something special, and nothing like the people here.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The complexity of sentences,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  she said, \'93\loch\f0 Paragraphs, pages\~\hich\f0 \'85\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Oh, Mina!\'94\loch\f0  said her mum.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Malcolm closed the book.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 Maybe you can make recommendations to us\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 , Mina,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he said. \'93\loch\f0 Now, Mrs. McKee, why don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t you leave Mina with us, and
\~\hich\f0 \'85\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes, I will,\'94\loch\f0  said Mrs. McKee.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She gave Mina a hug. She told her to have a nice day. She told her she\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d be back to pick her up that afternoon.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 As she walked away, Mina wanted to \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 weep like a four-year-old. She wanted to cry, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Take me away, Mummy! Take me away!\'94\loch\f0 
 But she just stood there, like a stone, silent and bereft.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 And other children started to arrive, and so the day began.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Among the others, there was Wilfred, who looked so ang\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
ry, whose brow was furrowed, who clenched his fists, who looked nobody but Malcolm in the eye. His nails had almost been bitten to nothing and two of his front teeth were gone. He smelt of dog.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 There was Alicia, who took a liking to Mina and sat by her all\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 day. Alicia was like a little creature. Her hands trembled, ever so slightly. Her fringe hung down over her eyes. She kept leaning forward so that her hair hung all around her head like a curtain. She spoke in little whispery breaths. \'93\loch\f0 
I like you, Mina. \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 C\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 an I sit with you at lunch, Mina?\'94\loch\f0  She stayed silent mostly, but sometimes Mina would hear her humming a low slow tune.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And there was Steepy, a skinny boy dressed all in green whose hands were covered in cuts and grazes. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Bloody roses, Malcolm,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he said. \'93\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
\hich\f0 Covered in bloody thorns, Malcolm. And bloody brambles. Like bloody knives, Malcolm.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  He grinned at Mina. \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s me bloody garden, Nina.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Mina,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Malcolm. He winked. \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s Steepy\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s aim to have the most abundant allotment in the land. It\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 s also his aim \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 to get a swearword into every sentence.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Bloody right, Malcolm,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Steepy. \'93\loch\f0 Couldn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t write a sentence to save me bloody life, but when it comes to swearing versatility\~\hich\f0 \'85
\~\loch\f0 And when it comes to works of bloody art\~\hich\f0 \'85\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 He lifted his shirt. There was a whole\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  garden tattooed on his chest: hedge, trees, dozens of flowers, butterflies, birds.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s just the bloody start. I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll get a bloody forest on me legs, mountains on me back, bloody sky on me bloody head.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Despite herself, and her determinationto stay cool \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 and distant, Mina leaned forward wide-eyed.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 But you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re just a boy!\'94\loch\f0  she heard herself saying.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 Aye, and I had it done when I wasn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t even twelve. Me uncle Eric done it. He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s a proper tattoo artist. They wanted to lock him up but they didn\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 t cos he\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s all I\hich\f0 \rquote \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ve got. But he can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t do no more tattoos on me till I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m sixteen. Then I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ll get the rest.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  He lowered his shirt again. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re messing up the bloody world, Mina. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re gonna burn it, blow it up, destroy it. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
re killing everything. Every lovely living thing\loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \rquote \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ll be extinct. But it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll all be on me, Mina. I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
ll be a bloody monument to everything that\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s gone.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s not as pessimistic as he makes out,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Malcolm. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Otherwise why bother with all the gardening?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 For love,\'94\loch\f0  said Steepy.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Bloody love, you mean,\'94\loch\f0  said Malcolm.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Aye. For bloody love.\'94\loch\f0  He looked at Mina.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s your story, then?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Mina shrugged.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s yours?\'94\loch\f0  she said.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve had it. What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s the point of school when there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s bloody gardening to be done?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 What you doing here\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 , then?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Hanging out with me mates. Like Malcolm. And Wilfie there.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Wilfred glared. He bared his teeth. Steepy raised his hand.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Down, boy,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 You are me bloody mate, Wilf, whether you want to be or not.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Wilf went on glaring, looking nothing lik\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 e a mate of anyone\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s at all.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Steepy winked at her.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s OK,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he whispered. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 As long as he keeps taking the pills.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The pills?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Aye. They wanted to put me on them as well. No bloody way! I said. Bloody pills!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Despite herself, she wanted to be his mate, \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
too. She did want to tell him her story, and to hear more about his, to talk about his garden and his tattoo, and to ask him how a bird that was born for joy could sit in a cage and sing, and to tell him about charms of goldfinches. She wanted to tell him
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 about playing with words on a page, and about the words she used to write on her own skin. And she wanted to tell him that they\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
d wanted to put her on pills, as well. But she didn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t. She went back to being distant. She turned away from him to Alicia, who \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
miled and touched her arm and softly hummed.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 So,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  said Malcolm. \'93\loch\f0 That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s getting to know you time over. Time for Maths. Sorry, Steepy. Bloody Maths.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 They did worksheets at the tables. A couple of assistants came in, Chloe and Joe. Chloe sat with Mina and \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 guided her through the problems. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
7 &#215; 6 is the same as 6 x __.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 123 &#215; 9 is the same as 9 x ___.\'94\loch\f0 
 They were easy. She heard Wilfred curse out loud and fling his pen across the room. He stood up and stormed to the window waving his fists. She saw\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
Malcolm gently guide him back to his task again. She heard Steepy speaking the answers to Malcolm and saw Malcolm writing them down. Alicia sat beside Mina and whispered how she always found sums so hard. Mina helped her and she saw the tears turn to smil
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 s as the solutions appeared to her. She also saw the thin scars on Alicia\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
s forearms. She touched one of them gently. Alicia flinched, then whispered very softly, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I used to cut meself, Mina. Not no more, though.\'94\loch\f0  Mina looked through Alicia\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s hanging frin
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 g\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
e into her eyes. She wanted to tell her about the day when she was in her tree, carving words into the bark with her knife. She had rested the blade on her own skin. She was almost at the point of carving a word into herself. She didn\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 t tell her, though.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 A\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 licia smiled sadly.
