 the world by Sophie Smith and written in my book by me. So maybe she is crackers, too, as she says she is.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s gone from the street with her friends.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 I write again, so shyly, so timidly.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Sophie\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s nice. I wish she had stayed a little longer. I wish I had\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  asked her to stay a little longer. Silly silly Mina!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 I think about what Sophie said about Mrs. Scullery and this gets me to thinking about Mrs. Scullery and I write again.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 A CONFESSION. OK, maybe Scullery wasn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t quite so horrible and screechy as I made he\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 r out to be. And maybe THE HEAD TEACHER wasn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
t quite so thick. And maybe they both showed a bit more understanding than I said they did. But when you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re writing stories, sometimes you just have to do these things. You have to EXAGGERATE, otherwise there w
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 uldn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t be any DRAMA. It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s just what writers DO!! OK?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Weird, how I can feel so frail and tiny sometimes, and other times so brave and bold and reckless and free, and\~\hich\f0 \'85\~\loch\f0 
Does everybody feel the same? When people get grown-up, do they always feel grown-up and \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 sensible and sorted out and\~\hich\f0 \'85\~\loch\f0 And do I want to feel grown-up? Do I want to stop feeling\~\hich\f0 \'85\~
\loch\f0 paradoxical, nonsensical? Do I want to stop being crackers? Do I want to be destrangified? O yes, sometimes I want nothing more \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  but it only lasts a moment, then oh\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 I want to be the strangest and crackerest of everybody, to be\~\hich\f0 \'85\~\loch\f0 O stop it, Mina! Sometimes I just think too much and ponder too much and\~\hich\f0 \'85\~\loch\f0 Stop it, I said!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Then there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s no time to squeak or squawk or wish or wonder anything else because a great big white v\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 an pulls into the street and stops outside Mr. Myers\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 s house. Then the blue car pulls up behind it and the family gets out. The mum has the baby all wrapped up in white in her arms.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Already?\'94\loch\f0  I whisper.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She looks along the street. She holds the baby close\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 like she wants to protect it from the world. The dad moves close and hugs them both. I hear the baby crying. She carries it inside. I imagine them in there, in the still-half-dilapidated house, the brand-new baby, the ancient neglected place.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Then the doo\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 rs of the van open and the dad and two burly men start carrying furniture into the house.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 The boy stays all alone, glaring at the earth, glaring at the sky. He holds a football under his arm.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What do you wish?\'94\loch\f0  I whisper to him, and of course there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s no w\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ay for him to hear.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 The new boy looks nice, I tell myself. Will I be brave enough to tell him that? Does he go to school? Of course he does.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 He bounces the ball, once, twice. He kicks it against the garden wall, once, twice. He glares at the street as if h\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 e hates it. Then he does follow his family and the furniture inside.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 I keep on watching. Then Mum\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s below me, smiling up at me.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I see the newcomers have arrived,\'94\loch\f0  she says.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 We look along towards Mr. Myers\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s house, which is no longer Mr. Myers\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s house.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 An\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 d the baby,\'94\loch\f0  I say.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The baby? Already?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Oh dear. I suppose they hoped to be more prepared. But they come when they come.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And the eggs have hatched as well,\'94\loch\f0  I say.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 So it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s the right time. It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a day of chicks and babies!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She reaches a hand tow\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ards me.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And listen to me, my baby.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 I think maybe you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re too much up there in your tree.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Too much in the tree?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 Yes. You should come down into the world a bit m\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ore. And you should come down and come for a walk with me.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 A walk to where?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 To wherever our feet might take us.\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 OK.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 I drop down, out of the tree. Then I put my finger to my lips.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Listen,\'94\loch\f0  I whisper.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 To what?\'94
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 Just listen. If we listen closely we\hich\f0 \rquote \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ll maybe hear the chicks cheeping in the nest. Maybe we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll even hear the baby.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 We listen closely, closely, closely. We stretch upwards, turn our heads towards the nest.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Hear them?\'94\loch\f0  I say.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 She shakes her head.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Me neither,\'94\loch\f0  I say.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 We grin at each other.
\par \loch\af0\dbch\af31505\hich\f0 \'93\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Maybe tomorrow,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  I say. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Take us somewhere, feet.\'94
\par 
